==English==
===Adverb===
[[Category:English idioms]]
'''red-handed'''

# In the act of wrongdoing.  Almost always used in the phrase ''to be caught red-handed''.

====Origin====
The phrase "(to be) caught red-handed" originates from a common practice used to protect and track money stolen from bank vaults.  Money (in particular, paper bills) are placed in a container or bag that also contains packets of indelible red ink or dye.  When stolen, these packets explode, coloring the container, money, and often the culprit's hands and clothes, a bright red.  This ink is very difficult to remove, making it easy to identify the criminal responsible for the robbery.  Businesses are also instructed not to accept money that has been colored with this dye.

While this banking practice is still used today, the phrase has come to mean, more generally, "(to be) caught in the act" of doing something wrong or illicit.  For example, a person caught in the middle of telling a lie can be "caught red-handed".

